{"batchcomplete":"","query":{"normalized":[{"from":"ferrous","to":"Ferrous"}],"pages":{"92523":{"pageid":92523,"ns":0,"title":"Ferrous","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"[[File:Iron(II) oxide.jpg|thumb|Ferrous oxide is more correctly called [[iron(II) oxide]].]]\n'''Ferrous''' (Fe<sup>2+</sup>), in [[chemistry]], indicates a [[divalent]] [[iron]] compound (+2 [[oxidation state]]), as opposed to [[ferric]], which indicates a [[trivalent]] iron compound (+3 oxidation state).<ref name=mw>{{Citation | title = Ferrous | url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ferrous | accessdate = 19 April 2008 | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]]}}.</ref> This usage has mostly been deprecated, with current [[IUPAC]] nomenclature having names containing the oxidation state in bracketed Roman numerals instead, such as [[iron(II) oxide]] for ferrous oxide (FeO), and [[iron(III) oxide]] for ferric oxide (Fe<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>). \n\n[[File:Pourbaix Diagram of Iron.svg|thumb|[[Pourbaix diagram]] of aqueous iron]]\n\nOutside chemistry, ferrous is an adjective used to indicate the presence of iron.<ref name=mw/> The word is derived from the [[Latin]] word ''{{lang|la|ferrum}}'' (\"iron\").<ref>{{Citation | title = Etymology (Meaning of Words) | date = 30 November 2007 | url = http://en.allexperts.com/q/Etymology-Meaning-Words-1474/Origin-word-1.htm | accessdate = 19 April 2008}}.</ref>  Ferrous metals include [[steel]] and [[pig iron]] (with a carbon content of a few percent) and [[alloy]]s of iron with other metals (such as stainless steel). Manipulation of atom-to-atom relationships between iron, carbon, and various alloying elements establishes the specific properties of ferrous metals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ferrous Alloys Properties|url=http://www.steelforge.com/literature/ferrousnon-ferrous-materials-textbook/ferrous-metals/|publisher=All Metals & Forge Group|accessdate=1 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe term ''[[non-ferrous]]'' is used to indicate [[metal]]s other than iron and alloys that do not contain an appreciable amount of iron.<ref>{{Citation | title = Non ferrous | url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/non%20ferrous | accessdate = 19 April 2008 | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]]}}.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ferromagnetism]]\n* [[Steelmaking]]\n* [[Ferrous metal recycling]]\n* [[Iron(II) oxide]] (ferrous oxide)\n* Ferrous chloride ([[iron(II) chloride]])\n* [[Iron(II) bromide]] (ferrous bromide)\n\n==References==\n{{wiktionary|ferrous|nonferrous}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{chemistry-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Iron]]"}]}}}}